column168: At the delivery the plant operator is responsible for unloading the contents of the trailer. The operator attempted to remove the dust cap from the product outlet valve  As he did a small amount of product was released to the containment area. None of the material came in contact with the operator and by the time an attempt to clean up the spilled material was made it evaporated. Less than 10 minutes.
column169: The delivery driver picked up this trailer loaded and had no idea there may have been product at the dust cap. During his inspection he did verify that all product valves were closed prior to transport. When speaking with the loading driver however is was reported that the shipper overfilled the trailer and had to remove some product before shipment. this could account for residual product at the dust cap if the shipped did not allow the material sufficient time to drain.

column168: At approximately 12/1/09 1330hrs, while enroute from Tampa, FL to San Juan, PR the chief mate of the Horizon Discovery, DI583S discovered a dripping (est. 1 drop every seven seconds) coming from the center body of the tank DCIU847022-5/TX2903010 from a drain line. Vessel notified Horizon Lines. Horizon Lines notified the shipper, Dana Container Inc, to get information on options to address and make arrangements to have one of their technician meet vessel on arrival. Ship took appropriate action to cord-off area, and place containment material to catch drippings. Horizon Lines notified the NRC as per 49 CFR 171.15 requirements.     As a result of multiple conversations between USCG San Juan, Horizon Lines, and Dana the following was set in motion:  1)Ship charged the fire system and hose in the tank’s locations on Hatch 11 above.    2)Dana Technician, Dana Haz Response Representative, and USCG made arrangements to meet vessel at pilot 12/3/09 0500hrs.  On 12/3/09, the Dana Technician found the center tank cover improperly seeded, because the top wing nuts were not equally tightened. This resulted in Hexanes’ drops escaping from the cover to the well and then to drain tube.  Once the wings nuts were equally and properly tighten, the dripping ceased. The tank was slosh tested, and it was found tight.
column169: In light of what came out the dialogue and the technician’s feedback, Dana Containers needs to review their procedures to make sure their personnel are fully aware of how to dog-down this center top cover with the wing nuts. They are to be equally tightened to properly seat the gasket and cover.  This would prevent any future re-occurrence.

column168: On 12/02/09 at 08:34 hrs., personnel in the CSXT Queensgate Yard in Cincinnati, OH discovered GATX17861, a loaded tank car of Xylenes, leaking from the bottom outlet valve cap. The car was isolated and the shipper, Marathon - Ashland was notified via their 24 hr toll free phone number (877-627-5463).  CSXT General Car Foreman and Sentinel Plus, Gary Frey, was dispatched to the scene and found product dripping from the bottom outlet cap. The issue identified and corrective actions were communicated to Mr. Roger Spring of Marathon - Ashland, phone # 606-921-6255.  The bottom outlet cap was tightened 1/4 turn and the release stopped.  Marathon - Ashland responded a CSXT emergency response contactor, Eagle/SWS to inspect the car and verify that the release had been stopped. Marathon - Ashland to obtain an FRA Movement Approval to move the tank car back to Catlettsburg, KY to be unloaded, so the bottom outlet valve can be inspected and repaired. This incident did require a special switching move.        Cause Code:  149  NARRI:  5(5+3+0) X (2+0) =  80

column168: Driver uses an product unloading system mounted on the cargo tank to transfer the  product to the customer's storage tank.  as the driver started to pump he noticed product leaking from under the pump housing.  The driver shut down and found a drain plug had been removed from the pump.   driver replaced the plug and completed delivery. The released material was contained with absorbent pads and boom.
column169: There are dedicated drivers assigned to this account. There are also fill in drivers who are trained on the equipment and the specific customer requirements. This particular trailer has a special delivery system that is different from most of the equipment the drivers are familiar with. This driver is one of the fill in drivers and is trained to this trailer. the one failure hear is that during the winter the dedicated drivers usually remove a drain plug after the tank is washed and replace it prior to the next load. The fill in driver in question was unaware of this procedure. and the dedicated driver failed to communicate this.   In the future a procedure will be put into place to communicate when in winter the plug is removed.

column168: WHILE UNLOADING THE PACKAGE THE UNLOADER REALIZED IT WAS LEAKING A WHITE POWDER.  PROGRESS WAS IMMEDIATELY STOPPED AND I WAS NOTIFIED. I SAW IT WAS A FIRE EXTINGUISHER AND PULLED THE PACKAGE TO THE SIDE FOR LATER INVESTIGATION.  WHILE INVESTIGATING LATER ON I REALIZED A SMALL AMOUNT OF THE POWDER HAD LEAKED OUT ONLY BECAUSE THE PIN WAS NOT HOLDING THE RELEASE VALVE SHUT. column168: A van trailer containing multiple shipments of hazardous waste was at the intransit storage facility at the intended waste disposal facility awaiting processing.  During a routine inspection, liquid was noticed leaking from the trailer.  A response crew was notified, donned the appropriate personal protective equipment and entered the trailer.  A 30 gallon drum had fallen over and the impact caused the bung to pop out of the lid, spilling the contents over the trailer floor.  The trailer was moved to a containment area where it was unloaded and decontaminated.  The gravel under the trailer was removed and all cleanup materials were placed into suitable salvage containers.  All clean up material was then disposed of at the intended waste management facility.
column169: Upon investigatin, it was discovered that upon arrival at the facility, the river parked the vehicle and removed his load securement devices.  Subsequent to this activity, the trailer was repositioned and it appears that the container tipped over during this activity.  IN order toprevent a recrrence, the individuals responsible for this operation have been re-instructed in the requrement that all load securement devices remain in place until the transport vehicle is parked and secured at the off-loading area.

column168: AT ABOUT 5:30 PM ON 12-8-09, DRIVER MICHAEL K. GUILLORY IN TRUCK 07007 AND TRAILER 10304, WAS WEST BOUND ON HWY 90, EAST OF JEANERETTE, LA, IN IBERIA PARISH AT HUBERTVILLE ROAD, WHEN A CAR PULLED ACROSS TWO LANES OF TRAFFIC, WENT THROUGH A CENTER SECTION IN A FOUR LANE AND CONTINUED UNTIL THE CAR WAS IN FRONT OF THE DRIVER. THE DRIVER NOTICED THE AUTO DID NOT STOP AND ATTEMPTED TO MANUEVER, SO AS NOT TO HIT THE AUTO. THE DRIVER OF THE TRUCK WAS IN THE RIGHT HAND LANE AND HARD BRAKED, BUT ENDED UP HITTING THE PASSENGER SIDE REAR OF AUTO. AT THAT TIME THE TRUCK BLEW A FRONT TIRE AND CAME TO REST ON A SOFT SHOULDER. THE SHOULDER GAVE WAY AND THE TRAILER ROLLED OVER ON ITS SIDE, ALONG WITH THE TRUCK. THE DRIVER THEN CALLED 911 AND REPORTED THE INCIDENT. DRIVER ALSO CALLED AND REPORTED TO THE COMPANY. LOUISIANA HAZARDOUS MATERIAL WERE CALLED AND A REPORT WAS FILED. NATIONAL HOTLINE WAS CALLED AND A REPORT WAS FILED. THERE WERE NO LEAKS OR CRACKS DISCOVERED ON THE TANK. THE ONLY DAMAGE TO THE CMTV WAS THE HOSE TUBE ON THE PASSENGER SIDE AND FENDER, ALONG WITH SOME WIRING AND CABLES. THERE WAS NO RELEASE OF PRODUCT OR SPILL. DUE TO THE VEHICLE ROLLING OVER, A COMPLETE INTERNAL AND EXTERNAL INSPECTION AND TEST WILL BE DONE TRAILER AND FILED WITH APPROPRIATE AGENCIES.
column169: DRIVER WILL BE RETRAINED IN DEFENSIVE DRIVING AND WILL BE MONITORED FOR A PERIOD OF TIME, AS DECIDED BY THE COMPANY SAFETY COUNCIL.    BETTER ACCIDENT INVESTIGATIVE PROCEDURES FOR STATE AND FEDERAL OFFICERS.

column168: A van trailer containing hazardous waste was picked up at a customer's site.  The customer had loaded the trailer.  When the driver arrived at the in transit storage facility he noticed a drum leaking when he was completing his post trip inspection.  A response crew was notified.  They donned the appropriate personal protective equipment, entered the trailer and overpacked the leaking drum into a suitable salvage container along with the material used in the clean up.  The leak was caused by the nut and bolt of the lock ring assembly of an adjoining drum puncturing the drum.  The trailer was then unloaded and placed back into service.  The original shipment was loaded onto another trailer and continued to the intended waste disposal facility.  Illinois Emergency Management Authority was notified and assigned case #H20091334 to the incident.
column169: At the time the shipment was accepted for transportation, the driver inspected the load and did not identfy any issues.  It is believed that during transportation, one container shifted allowing it to strike the container next to it causing a small puncture in the body of the container.  In order to prevent a recurrence, the shipper has been notified  and advised that when loading a van trailer, due care and attention must be used to insure that each container is completely impolized to prevent movement in any dircetion.  In addition, care must be taken when loading containers that have protrucing closure devices to insure these devices annot negativelyimpact other lading.  The driver was also re-instructed to physically inspect the load secirement and containr placement before accepting a container for transportation.

column168: While loading a shipment of hazardous material at the customer's dock, the driver tipped back the drum dolly which contained the 30 gallon drum.  The bung was not properly closed and a small amount of material leaked out onto the snow covered ground.  The drum was uprighted and the contaminated snow was placed into the drum.  The driver closed the drum using the manufacturer's closure instructions using his torque wrench.  The shipment continued to the intended waste disposal facility without further incident.
column169: The cause of the incident is believed to have occured due to two factors.  The shipper did not adequately close the container and the driver did not insn=pect the closure device before initiating the loading process.  In order to prevent a recirrence, the shipper has been advised to insure that every container is closed pursuant to the manufacturer's closure instructions before offering for transportaiton.  In addition, the driver has been re-instructed to inspect each container before it is moved in preparation for loading onto a transport vehicle.

column168: The IBC was being moved from a storage area to a shipment staging area with a lift truck. The IBC slid off the forks of the lift truck as it was turning to back down an incline. One leg of the IBC came to rest on level ground while three others came to rest on the incline. This caused the IBC to tip over on its side. The impact with the concrete surface caused the side and the top of the IBC to split releasing the contents. Surface drains in the path of the liquid flow were protected using bags of Sodium Carbonate to form a barrier and prevent entry. Collection of the liquid on the concrete surface bgan using a pump to transfer the material to IBC's and drums. Once the liquid was collected, the Sodium Carbonate used as a barrier and for neutralization was collected and containerized. The release occurred at approximately 3:00 pm and the area was secured at 7:15 pm.
column169: All IBC's stored in this area have been relocated to a new storage location with a level surface.  The lift truck operator will be re-trained.

Hoose, noted product coming from the manway area and adhering to the side of tank car GATX 3385 (L/ FLAMMABLE LIQUID, N.O.S. - ROSIN SOLUTION) while observing switching operations at CN Glenn Yard, Chicago, IL. All appropriate departments notified. CN Hazmat Team responded noting the manway gasket had become disengaged and damaged allowing product to be released during movement. New manway gasket installed. Mr Hoose also noted that the collar to the manway security swing bolt located to the left of the manway handle was corroded and had rusted free preventing the manway to be properly secured for transportation. Shipper notified to correct or seek FRA Movement Approval.
column169: No additional comments.

column168: At the delivery point the plant operator must remove the dust cap from the cargo tank product outlet valve in order to secure a sample. There was a small amount of residual product trapped between the external valve and the dust cap and when the operator attempted to remove the cap some product spilled onto the concrete pad.   Product was cleaned up by the operator.
column169: Not sure how the product become trapped between the external valve and the dust cap.  The trailer is top loaded There is the possibility that the trailer was overloaded and some material had to be removed prior shipment. The trailer was cleaned after delivery and both the internal and external valves passed a vacuum test. The driver also confirmed that the valves were tightly closed during his pre trip inspection prior to delivery.  The driver is not required to assist the operator in sampling and did not witness  the release. He was informed by the operator after the fact.  Because the driver did not actually witness the event it is difficult to comment on why there was a spill. There could have been residual product left in the valve from the shipper. The operator could have made a procedure error.

column42: PAINT INCLUDING PAINT, LACQUER, ENAMEL, STAIN, SHELLAC SOLUTIONS, VARNISH, POLISH, LIQUID FILLER AND LIQUID LACQUER BASE
column168: When unloading freight from trailer material handler discover a box that had been crushed inbetween two pallets. Apparently the box was staged on top of one of the pallets that it was crushed by unsecured and as a result in fell and got crushed in transit. When it was crushed it caused one of the inner containers to fail and contribute to the unintentional release. Spilled material was cleaned with sorbent materials and placed into a recovery container along with the damaged container.
column169: We are continuously training and reminding our employees of the importance of securing freight to prevent relative motion in transit to try and prevent these types of unintentional releases.

column168: When unloading a double stacked pallet from trailer, forklift operator pulled backwards with his forklift in such a way that it caused the top pallet to fall off the bottom one. When this happened it fell to the floor causing one of the cans in one of the boxes to 'pop' its lid and contribute to the unintentional release. Spilled material was cleaned with sorbent material and placed into a recovery container along with the damaged box/can.
column169: Forklift operator should have broken down the pallets beore trying to remove the both of them double-stacked.

column168: When unloading freight from trailer material handler found a pallet of paint that had a very small puddle of paint underneath it. Further investigation revealed that a nail from the pallet that the paint was staged on had punctured the bottom of one pail contributing to the unintentional release. Spilled material was cleaned with sorbent material and placed into a recovery container along with the damaged pail.

FED-EX shipment 793088891115 from BAE Minneaplois MN, contains 3 Hazard classes in one pipe shipment (1.4E, 1.4C, and 1.4S).  Although all Hazard classes are compatible they cannot be combined in one container unless the UN numbers are the same.  This container has 3 different UN #'s  shipped in one pipe which should have used a single UN0471, 1.4E exemption, and the 1.4S and 1.4C shipped separately.      Crate label indicates 3.6 gram net explosive weight.  Actual contents 18.2 grams.

column168: A box truck containing hazardous waste was en route to the intended waste management facility.  During the course of the trip, the driver made a routine stop at Clean Harbor's in transit storage facility for the purpose of consolidating less than truckload quantities of hazardous waste onto a single transport vehicle for continued transportation. The load was checked during each required load check for the 350 mile trip without incident.  Upon arrival at the facility, the load was checked and no leaks were found.  The next morning, when the door to the truck was opened, it was found to have a leaking container from a UN rated fiberboard box.  The employee donned the appropriate personal protective equipment and found a glass bottle inside the box had broken.  The remaining material was placed into a suitable salvage container along with the soaked vermiculite, cardboard box and cleanup materials.  The shipment was then loaded onto a trailer for the intended waste disposal facility.
column169: During the clean-up activities, it was discovered that the inner container was packaged using vermuculite as a cushining and absorbant material but did not adequatley protect the container from damage during transportation.  In order to prevent a recurrence, the individual responsible for preparing the package was re-instructed in the proper requirements for containerizing and securing combination packages for transportation.

A van trailer was dispatched to a customer location to accept for transportation IBC's contain sodium hydroxide solution.  During the loading operation, the individual positioning the containers onto the van trailer struck the bottom valve of one IBC with a second container allowing the valve to crack.  The contents of the IBC drained onto the floor of the van trailer and the loading area where the vehicle was positioned.  Facility personnel activiate the emergency response team and, wearing appropriate protective equipment, initiated an internal response.  All free liquid was absorbed with a suitable absorbent material and containerized.  In addition, the impacted soil and gravel where the trailer was parked was remediated and this material was also containerized.  The trailer itself was decontaminated and all material collected from this operation were placed in the containers with the absorbents and clean-up debris.  All waste generated as a result of this incident was placed into storage pending off-site disposal.  The damaged container was placed out of service pending a repair vs. disposal decision.
column169: An inspection of the container identified that a section of ancillary piping had not been removed from the IBC before initiating the loading procedure.  This piping was struck damaging the valve and allowing the product to escaped from the package.  In order to prevent a recurrence, the shipper has been advised to insure that before offering a container for transportation that all closure devices are in place according to the manufacturer's specification.  In addition, the driver will be re-trained in the steps that must be taken to inspect each container before it is accepted for transportation.  He/she must insure that each container accepted has any ancillary devices removed before accepting for transportation.

CUSTOMS ALLOWED ME TO VIEW THE SHIPMENT ON 11/23/2009 AND ASSURED THAT IT WOULD NOT FORWARD. IT WAS NOT OPENED AT THAT TIME.ON 11/24/2009 CUSTOMS ALLOWED ME TO OPEN THE PACKAGE. BEFORE REACHING THE CONTENTS,THE ODOR OF RUBBING ALCOHOL WAS EVIDENT. I CLOSED THE PACKAGE AND IT WAS TAPED SHUT.CUSTOMS RELEASED THE SHIPMENT ON 12/04/2009. SPILL TECHNICIANS BEN SHIDELER AND JESSE FIFE RESPONDED. THE SPILL TECHNICIANS REMOVED THE SHIPMENT FROM THE AREA FOR FURTHER INVESTIGATION. THE PACKAGE WAS FOUND TO CONTAIN 2 X 100 mL PLASTIC BOTTLES PACKED IN A PLASTIC ZIP LOCK BAG, INSIDE OF A SECOND PLASTIC BAG, INSIDE A FIBREBOARD BOX, INSIDE A PLASTIC DHL EXPRESS BAG. THE SHIPMENT DID NOT LEAK-ODOR ONLY. MSDS PROVIDED BY THECONSIGNEE MATCHED CONTENTS. TRACKING INDICATES INITIAL TRANSPORTATION BY AIR.

column168: A van trailer containing hazardous waste arrived at the intransit storage facility for unloading onto the dock for ultimate reloading onto a trailer destined for the intended waste disposal facility.  At the time of pickup, all drums were inspected and none were found to be leaking. When doing his required post trip inspection, the driver noticed a small amount of material on the top of one of the drums.  Dock personnel donned the appropriate personal protective equipment and determined that the bung gasket of the leaking drum was defective.  The waste was contained to the top of the drum and was cleaned up using an absorbent material and put back into the drum.  The bung and gasket of the offending drum were replaced.  The shipment was then loaded onto a trailer for the intended waste disposal facility.  The incident was reported to the Louisiana State Police, incident number 09-06898.
column169: The shipper was notified of the incident and all drivers will be cautioned to inspect all drums more closely for integrity and proper closure prior to acceptance for transportation.

column168: A Con-way Freight tractor pulling two semi-trailers was headed E/B on 1-10 at MM 99, near Tonapah, AZ when the driver lost control of his vehicle and overturned all three units. Although the event did not result in an unintentional release of a hazardous material, both E/B lanes of 1-10 were blocked. Belfor Environmental, an emergency response vendor was called to the scene to determine if an unintentional release of a hazardous material had occurred. Onceit was determined there was no release of the hazardous material on board, a towing company up-righted the equipment and removed it from the scene, opening up the E/B lanes of 1-10 for traffic to resume. The hazardous material on board remained intact and undamaged.
column169: Driver error, disciplinary action to be implemented.

column58: Pressure Relief Valve or Device - Reclosing
column168: On 12/10/09 at 21:12 hrs., personnel in the CSXT Hialeah yard in Miami, FL discovered DGIX 33544, a loaded tank car of Liquefied Petroleum Gases, releasing vapors.  The car was isolated and the shipper, Crosstex Processing Services, was notified via CHEMTREC (Report #2009-12-10-00202).  Eagle/SWS, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found the pressure relief device emitting vapors.  Eagle/SWS personnel installed a pressure gauge on the vapor valve and found that the container had 280 PSI.  In addition, Eagle/SWS representatives checked the gauging device on the car and found that the car had 8" of outage.  The tank car was determined to be overloaded and Crosstex Procesing Services was notified of the findings.  Crosstrex arranged for the consignee to respond and off-load approximately 1,400 gallons of product.  After off-loading the excess product, the pressure in the railcar dropped to 132 pounds.  Once the car was secured, it was released for transportation.      An AAR QA Program 7.1 Nonconformance Report will not be required for this incident.  NOTE:  This incident did require a special shipping move.    Cause Code:  419  NARRI:  5 (5+5+0) X (2+0) = 100
column169: No additional comments.

column42: PETROLEUM DISTILLATES, N.O.S. OR PETROLEUM PRODUCTS, N.O.S.
column168: On12/20/09 at 01:20 hrs., personnel in the CSXT Gentilly Yard in New Orleans, LA, discovered NATX 29593, a loaded tank car of Petroleum Distillates, N.O.S. leaking from the liquid line valve. The car was isolated and the shipper, Calumet Lubricants, was notifed via CHEMTREC (Report #2009-1220-00003).  The Louisiana State Police, Louisiana DEQ, and the local fire department were also notified.  Eagle/SWS, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found that the liquid line valve assembly was loose. The valve was tightened 3/4 of a turn to stop the leak. The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper representative, Darwin Parker, cell phone #318-393-4904. Contractor personnel secured the leak, decontaminated the car and cleaned up the spilled material.  The car was released for transport. This incident did require a special switching move.     Cause Code: 282  NARRI:  5 (5+5+0) X (2+0) = 100
column169: Spoke with Darwin Parker, 318-393-4904, of Calumet Lubricants about what was found so he could discuss with the loaders. Also suggested that he speak with the customer so they could discuss with the unloaders.

column168: On 12/27/09 at 12:40 hours, personnel in the CSXT Willard Terminal in Willard, OH discovered TILX 190315, a loaded tank car of N-propanol, leaking from the bottom outlet of the car. The car was moved and isolated over the spill pan to contain the leak. The shipper was notified via CHEMTREC (Report #20091212700024) and the Willard, OH Police Department was notified as well. Eagle/SWS, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene to make repairs.  Upon arrival, ECESI personnel discovered product leaking from the bottom outlet nozzle and cap. The bottom outlet valve was not fully closed and the bottom outlet cap was less than tool tight. ECESI personnel closed the valve, tightened the cap and the leak stopped.  The car was released for transportation. This incident did require a special switching move.        Cause Code:  148  NARRI: 5(5+3+0) X (2+0) = 80
column169: No additional comments.

column42: VEHICLE, FLAMMABLE GAS POWERED OR VEHICLE, FUEL CELL, FLAMMABLE GAS POWERED
column168: On December 10th, 2009 during the inspection of cargo due to the container exceeding the allowable weight it can carry, the carrier (Seaboard Marine) noticed that container TGHU748400 was carrying non-hazardous as well as hazardous cargo including forklifts, loose propane tanks and loose batteries. In addition to the cargo being over-weight, it was also noticed that the cargo lacked the adequate blocking and bracing as required by 49CFR part 176. The container was immediately placed on "Hold" status and the shipper was advised of the finding. The shipper was asked to split the cargo into two containers, one containing the hazardous cargo and the other container the non-hazardous items. The shipper was also asked to properly stow and brace the cargo, and finally to properly document, mark, label and placard the container with the hazardous cargo. During the days that it took to coordinate this process, the USCG inspected and subsequently issued a notice of discrepancy. The cargo was properly declared, blocked, braced and released for transport by USCG and subsequently by carrier.

column42: PHOSPHORUS, WHITE OR YELLOW DRY OR UNDER WATER OR IN SOLUTION
column168: Yard personnel at the Union Pacific Railroad at Avondale, LA observed smoke and flame emitting form the deck of flatcar GIMX 10002.  The car was located on track 19 and was loaded with three intermodal tank containers, EXFU 143148, TRLU 027774 and EXFU 144208. The tank containers contained residue: last contained phosphorus, yellow, under water, class 4.1 (6.1), UN1381, PG I. Due to the smoke, visibility was impaired and it was believed that one or more of the tank containers was leaking with the phosphorus spontaneously igniting as it dried on the deck of the flatcar.  The flat car was isolated onto the rip track lead without incident and appropriate emergency notifications were completed.  Rail traffic was halted in the area, including the mainline. The mainline was shutdown approximately 2 hours.  Inspection was conducted by response personnel and determined that all of the tank containers were secure and had not been leaking. In addition, the smoke and flame was emitting from drying phosphorus that was on the deck of the flatcar. The source of the phosphorus was unknown, but it was speculated that it had been spillage from a previous loading event at Soda Springs, ID. It was believed that snow and ice might have kept the spillage from drying and igniting until in Avondale.  The spillage amount was estimated to be less than 2 ounces. A consensus was established that the spillage would be remediated and removed on site using an accelerated thermally enhanced combustion process.    The three loaded tank containers (EXFU 027998, EXFU 143230, TRLU 027729) containing phosphorus, yellow, under water that had been recently unloaded from flat car GIMX 10002 were inspected at the port of New Orleans, LA.  Inspections were also performed on approximately 30 other tank containers at the Port, and determined that none of them were leaking. However, tank container TRLU 027729 was observed with discoloration on the outer jacket, and is suspected as being the source of the phosphorus on flatcar GIMX 10002.

column168: The transporter, Quality Carriers (QC), was leaving the plant with TW-6634 loaded with hazardous waste. When the QC driver stopped at the main gate, the load sloshed forward and allowed a small amount of waste to leak from the manway washout nozzle into the crash box. The material drained down the drain tube and onto the pavement as he was pulling through the main gate, leaving approximately a 40 foot line of drips. Duration of material draining from drain tube was approximately 2 minutes. Site Security Services called the Tank Farm Advisor who contacted the tank farm operator. When the tank farm operator arrived at the truck, the Quality Carriers' driver had already opened, checked gasket and reclosed the manway with hammer. The driver did the same with the washout cap in the crashbox. (A washout cap seals a 3" nozzle on the top centerline of a tank trailer. There are usually multiple nozzles along the top of a tank wagon that are used when the tank wagon needs to be cleaned.) The QC driver also cleaned the crashbox with a cleanup pad. The QC driver indicated that the washout cap had leaked. Once the spill had been cleaned up, the QC driver tested the load for leaks by pulling forward and backing up rapidly several times and there was no sign of leaks.The root cause of the leak was a dent in the end of the pipe (washout nozzle) where the cap gasket is supposed to seat.
column169: Quality Carriers was notified of the damaged washout nozzle, and Tank Wagon #6634 was returned to their shop for repairs.Cherokee Pharmaceuticals will review its procedures with loading operators focusing on the need to test loaded containers for leaks prior to offering for transportation.

column168: Semi-tractor trailer pulling a loaded specification cargo tank left roadway resulting In a rollover accident  A tire on the right side of the steering axle of the truck blew out causing loss of vehicle control. Truck then struck an unoccupied vehicle that was parked along the shoulder of 1-75 at or near mile marker 194. Tractor-trailer then went into ditch and rolled in a wooded area next to the interstate. An unknown, notified 911 operator which triggered police and fire response. Fire was caused by leaking diesel fuel from the truck. Fire department from Forsyth GA extinguished the fire.  Carrier was notified of accident by the truck driver. Carrier then notified the shipper, Chemtrec, and NRC. Fire Department was unwilling to approach the tanker to report a leak or no leak condition. Carrier then contracted First Environmental Inc. to respond, investigate, and to conduct any clean-up of materials present.  Interstate 1-75 was dosed on the south bound lanes for a period of 10 hours during which time recovery of vehicles was performed, and a transload of the hazardous material to another specification cargo tank for transport was conducted. The initial cargo tank was not leaking, but was not road worthy following the rollover accident.  First Environmental cleaned up the area induding removal of top soils containing engine oil, anti-freeze, and diesel fuel. Gradient of the ditch and indine to the interstate was replaced with dean backfill materials to GA highway department standards.  Incident occurring at 00:15 on 12/1412009 was completed at 17:00.
column169: We can make no recommendations to prevent such an occurrence. However the lack of training and cooperation on the part of the Forsyth Fire Department prohibited the process of evaluating the incident severity, removal of equipment, and remediation of the location by several hours.

column169: INSPECT AREAS THOROUGHLY TO ENSURE UNSAFE CONDITIONS ARE NOT PRESENT TO AVOID EASY DAMAGING TO PACKAGES OF DRUMS, PAILS, TOTES, BAGS AND OTHER PACKAGING CONTAINING HAZARDOUS MATERIALS OR CHEMICALS.  CHECK THE FLOORS FTRAILER TO ENSURE NO SHARP OBJECTS, NAILS, PIECES OF WOOD, DAMAGED PALLETS ARE PROTRUDING THAT COULD CAUSE EASY DAMAGE TO DRUMS, PAILS, BAGS TOTES AND OTHER PACKAGINGS. column14: 9 Mi. W. of Cortez on Cty rd G
column168: Our tractor/trailer was traveling in a snow storm when the trailer slid off the road into the ditch.  Two wreckers were called to get the unit out of the ditch.  We got permission from the State of Colorado Haz-mat Division to vent the remaining oxygen off the trailer to minimize damage to the trailer and to make the extraction easier for the wreckers.  Approximately 205,000 cubic feet (16,961 pounds) of oxygen was released.  Unit was towed 1 mile to our customer's location by the wrecker and after the storm abated, the tractor was driven back to Albuquerque.  Trailer is still in Cortez getting repaired for transport back to Albuquerque.
column169: This incident prompted us to re-educate all of our drivers in the hazards of winter driving, and other inclement weather driving, expecially in the more mountainous areas that we travel into.

NATIONAL VACCUM WAS DISPATCHED TO THE SCENE AND HANDLED THE REMEDIATION.  NO FURTHER ENVIRONMENTAL IMPACT IS EXPECTED.  THIS RELEASE WAS CAUSED SOLEY BY MECHANICAL ISSUES WITH THE UNDERGROUND STORAGE TANK.

column168: ON 12-06-09 PIEDMONT TRANSPORT DRIVER RONNIE LEE ARRIVED TO THE LOCATION "BUY AND GO # AT 27 01 S. SANDERS STREET RALEIGH, NC WITH 8,498 GALLONS OF REGULAR 87.  DRIVER STARTED UNLOADING WHEN SUDDENLY GASOLINE STARTED TO COME OUT OF A "PROBE WELL" (MAN WAY) LOCATED IN THE PARKING LOT.  APPROXIMATELY 30 TO 50 GALLONS CAME OUT OF THE WELL.  DRIVER STOPPED THE FLOW AND IMMEDIATELY STARTED THE PROCEDURE TO CONTAIN THE SPILL.  AS IT WAS GOING DOWN HILL TOWARDS THE STREET, IT REACHED THE STORM DRAIN.  FIRE DEPARTMENT WAS CALL AND CLEAN UP CREW.  (EASTERN ENVIRONMENTAL MANAGEMENT)  THE INVESTIGATION FOUND OUT THAT THE "PROBE CAP INSIDE THE WELL" WAS NOT CLOSE OR TIGHT ENOUGH AND THE "PROBE CAP" CAME LOOSE ALLOWING THE GASOLINE TO COME OUT OF IT.
column169: THE CUSTOMER SHOULD MAINTAIN THE TANKS IN BETTER CONDITIONS AND REQUIRE TO THEIR REPAIR OR MAINTENANCE COMPANY TO ENSURE THAT ALL FITTINGS, CAPS, INLETS AND OUTLETS ARE CLOSE/TIGHT AFTER ANY WORK HAS BEEN DONE.

column168: OUR DRIVER ARRIVED AT THE PLANT AT 9:30 AND SET UP EVERYTHING FOR OFF LOADING.  HE STARTED PUMPING OFF HIS LOAD USING THE PUMP ON HIS TRACTOR.  AFTER UNLOADING FOR APPROXIMATELY 1 HOUR, THE DRIVER NOTICED A PROBLEM WITH THE DISCHARGE HOSE.  THE FITTING AT THE END OF THE HOSE SEPARATED FROM THE END OF THE HOSE AND PRODUCT SPILLED ONTO THE GROUND.  THE DRIVER NOTICED THIS AND IMMEDIATELY SHUT THE PUMP DOWN.  IT WAS DETERMINATE THAT ABOUT 40 GALLONS SPILLED ONTO THE GROUND WHICH WAS CONTAINED IN A CONTAINMENT AREA.  THE CUSTOMER POURED SPEEDY DRY ON THE CONTAMINATED AREA ANC CONTAINED THE SPILL.  THEY THEN CALLED A FIRM BY THE NAME OF STAT INCORPORATED TO CLEAN UP THE AREA.  THE INCIDENT WAS REPORTED TO CHEMTREC.  THIS INCIDENT OCCURRED BECAUSE OF A HOSE FAILURE.  THERE ARE 2 CLAMPS ON THE HOSE END THAT SECURE THE HOSE TO THE COUPLING.  SOMEHOW THE BANDS FAILED AND THE HOSE SEPARATED FROM THE FITTING.
column169: LANGER TRANSPORT WILL GO THROUGH OUR INVENTORY OF HOSES AND INSPECTING THEM IN AN EFFORT TO PREVENT THIS PROBLEM FROM HAPPENING AGAIN.  WE WILL ALSO BE GOING BACK TO THE MANUFACTURER OF THE HOSE TO INFORM THEM ABOUT THE PROBLEM WE HAD AS THIS LOOKS LIKE A MANUFACTURING DEFECT.

column168: BNSF crews working in the railyard reported an ammonia type odor in the railyard. The yard crews ceased working and employees were sheltered until the odor source was located. BNSF responders found GATX 9305 (DOT 112J340W tank car) in the railyard to be the source of the stench. The responders inspected GATX 9305 finding all valves closed and fittings secure. No residue product vapor release was pinpointed using a soapy leak detection solution. The shipper was requested to assist and GATX 9305 was cordoned-off in the railyard. The shipper responder verified the securement of GATX 9305 with the exception of the A-end liquid valve's closure plug. The shipper responder's leak detection solution indicated a slight vapor escape at this closure plug with no liquid release. This plug was removed, threads cleaned, new sealant applied to threads, reinserted and tool tightened. After securement was completed by 0930 hrs. CST, 12/04/09, no further residue product odor was evident.

column62: Forklift Accident; Impact with Sharp or Protruding Object (e.g., nails)
column168: Forklift operator was unloading this shipment from his trailer. When the forklift operator picked up the pallet, a loose board or slat on the leading edge of the pallet was pushed inward and punctured one of four metal one gallon containers in the bottom left side carton. The forklift operator then broke the pallet down and removed the leaking carton and turned it upside down to reduce leakage. Floor dry was placed on the trailer floor and on the dock where the leakage had accumulated, about one half gallon total. The leaking carton was then placed inside a recovery drum, The leaking carton consists of one leaking one gallon container (about half full) and three one gallon containers which were not damaged or leaking but had liquid spilled on them from the one damaged container. The floor dry placed on the liquid which had leaked was swept up and was also placed in the same recovery drum. The size of the puncture hole in the outer carton was approximately one inch long. The container inside the carton which had leaked was dented and had a small puncture hole toward the bottom of the container.
column169: Any hazardous materials that is shipped on pallets should be placed on strong, sturdy pallets. There should not be any loose boards on the pallet that might damage the hazardous material product. Dock employees should examine pallets of hazardous materials prior to unloading to verify the product is secure on the pallet and that there are no loose boards or other sharp objects which could damage the shipment during unloading. Dockworkers should take extra precaution whenever handling any hazardous material shipment.

column168: Darrell Santillanes - F3401, was loading shipment 936-253231 on trailer 313-3466 at door 57 atthe USD Service Center when he pushed this shipment into another pallet causing it to crush and puncture a 5-Gallon Pail containing Adhesives, 3 UN1133 PG II. Chemtrec was contacted through the direction of the shipper BOL and the Linehaul Safety Department. I spoke to Kevin Runnels - Chemtrec Report Number: 2009123000009. The spilled product was cleaned up following Section 6 of the product's MSDS. Absorbent was used and the container, product, and absorbent were all placed into a salvage drum.
column169: After the incident occurred, I pulled Darrell aside and discussed what could have been done differently to prevent this from happening. I set the expectation of what I want to see happen in the future following I.C.E. principles so incidences like these do not reoccur. I will follow up with an I/R because this is the first incident he's had regarding spills and improper loading. I will also require him to be retrained using I.C.E. principles to help prevent this from happening again.

column168: The vehicle incurred a right side, steer tire failure.  The XATA crash data report indicates that the driver immediately removed his foot from the throttle and applied his brakes.  As the vehicle decelerated, the application of the brakes caused the vehicle to move to the right-side off the highway, crossing the paved shoulder on to the slope of a drainage ditch that tilted the vehicle beyond its center of gravity causing it to rollover coming to rest on the driver’s side.    Three (3) ammonium nitrate bin lids were torn off during the roll, even though they were securely locked.  The driver was seat belted properly during the crash, and subsequently was able to climb out of the passenger’s side of the vehicle.  9-1-1 was notified, and subsequently the driver’s terminal manager was notified of the incident.  The driver’s terminal manager notified the company, which notified ERTS, the company’s 24-hr spill consultant who dispatched Wench Associates, a qualified spill contractor to the scene.  ERTS called the National Response Center at 4:00 PM as required by the HMR.    The release occurred at 3:24 PM EST and the recovery was concluded at approximately 9:00 PM EST.  Wench Associates contained and cleaned up the spill working in coordination with State Highway officials and Local First Responders.
column169: The company hired Valley Technical Services, a crash reconstruction investigation company (VTS), who within 48-hrs after the crash, investigated the crash scene and vehicle involved.  The failed steer tire was shipped from MN to OH for professional dismount by Goodyear Wingfoot for close examination to determine the root cause of the failure.      VTS’s investigation concluded that a sidewall bruise on the radial tire preconditioned the steer axle tire failure.  VTS also indicated that the driver’s actions, applying the brakes immediately after the failure, most likely caused the vehicle to move off the hard road surface into the drainage ditch.      The company will undertake the following actions to mitigate this type of incident:    1. Conduct Communications Meetings with drivers to review accident findings, conclusions and recommendations, and specific countermeasures to mitigate rollovers, and review importance of pre-trip and post-trip tire inspections.    2. Develop and implement certain policies and procedures regarding the use of its vehicles in off-road conditions or other locations where sidewall bruises could occur.      3. Review with the vehicle body manufacturer, countermeasures regarding protection of ammonium nitrate bin lids that would mitigate the probability of a spill.

column168: When unloading freight from trailer material handler discovered a pail that had leaked in transit from the top lid closure. No action contributed to this failure other than a loose lid closure. Spilled material was cleaned with sorbent and placed into a recovery container along with the leaking pail.

When driver went to deliver freight at consignee location he discovered the pail was leaking from the bottom. The driver did not observe this unintentional release at a prior delivery right down the road. Further investigation revealed that there was a small crack on the bottom of the pail. The pail was secured to a pallet during the course of transportation and have no direct cause or action that contributed to this unintentional release. Spilled material was cleaned with sorbent material and placed into a recovery container along with the damaged container.

column168: A BNSF yard switch crew reported a product odor emanating from PSPX 21893 (DOT 105A300W tank car) in the railyard. PSPX 21893 was cordoned off and all employees relocated from this area. BNSF and contract responders were summoned. Contract responders inspecting PSPX 21893 reported finding a small amount of spillage under the A-end liquid line valve handle. Further inspection revealed a loose packing gland nut on the A-end liquid line valve stem. The responders tightened this valve stem packing nut. All other fittings were inspected and found secure. A bleach/water solution was used to wash down the valve housing area. Responders rechecked all valves and fittings using an air monitoring device and no product detection registered. The valve housing cover was resealed with seal numbered 433368. Response was concluded by 1030 CST, 12/21/09.

column168: ADMX 29553 (DOT 111A100W1 tank car) was reported dripping product from its bottom outlet valve (BOV) area in the railyard. ADMX 29553 was carefully moved and placed over the facility's containment pit awaiting further inspection. On 12/22/09, BNSF contract responders inspected ADMX 29553 and reported finding the cause of the leak as loose BOV mounting flange nuts at the base of this bottom operated BOV. Responders preceded to tool tighten all flange nuts and after the flange connection was secured, product drips ceased. Securement was completed by 1000 hrs. CST, 12/22/09. Afterwards, responders continued to monitor ADMX 29553 and monitoring was concluded after no further product dripping from the BOV was evident. Spillage within the containment pit evaporated atop a layer of ice that had covered the bottom of the containment pit.

column169: PAILS CONTAINING LIQUIDS, HAZARDOUS MATERIALS AND CHEMICALS MUST BE SAFELY CHECKED TO INSURE NOTHING IS ALLOWED TO LEAK OUT. WHEN HANDLING AND MOVING PAILS AND DRUMS, KNOW THE SURROUNDINGS TO ENSURE PRODUCT IS NOT EASILY DAMAGED. RETRAINING IN WORK METHODS ON PROPER AND SAFE LOADING AND HANDLING OF HAZARDOUS MATERIALS, LIQUIDS AND CHEMICALS. RECURRENT TRAINING IN HAZARDOUS MATERIALS. WHEN LOADING NOTE THAT BAGS, PAILS OR DRUMS OF LIQUIDS AHEAD. HEAVY FREIGHT LOADED ON THE BOTTOM, LIGHT FREIGHT ON TOP! USE PLENTY OF CUSHIONING BETWEEN LAYERS OF FREIGHT. DO NOT LOAD HEAVY FREIGHT ON TOP OF HAZARDOUS MATERIALS. FREIGHT MUST BE SECURELY BLOCKED AND BRACED BEFORE ALLOWING TO MOVE IN TRANSIT! USE OTHER FREIGHT TO SECURE FREIGHT.

column168: A BNSF train was stopped in emergency on BNSF main track 2 (approximately 7 miles east of Moorcroft, WY) with the head 22 railcars derailed after traversing a broken rail. Derailed equipment included SIRX 95031 (AAR C114 three compartment covered hopper) that derailed on its side. The top hatchways of SIRX 95031 were jarred open releasing product. SIRX 95031 sustained structure damages that included a structure split starting at the A-end top corner. Product released from this compromised area also. The hatchways were closed and the compromised portions of SIRX 95031 were plugged to prohibit further product release. Spillage on the ground was excavated, stockpiled and covered for appropriate future disposal at a nearby landfill. Disposal activities are scheduled to commence during the week of 1/18/2010. The product remaining within SIRX 95031 was transferred into trucks and delivered to the consignee between 12/16 - 12/18/09.

column169: PAILS CONTAINING LIQUIDS, HAZARDOUS MATERIALS AND CHEMICALS MUST BE SAFELY CHECKED TO INSURE NOTHING IS ALLOWED TO LEAK OUT. THE PACKAGINGS MUST BE COMPLETELY SHROUDED, BLOCKED AND BRACED BY USING DUNNAGE, PLYWOOD AND OR MTY PALLETS. WHEN HANDLING AND MOVING PAILS AND DRUMS, KNOW THE SURROUNDINGS TO ENSURE PRODUCT IS NOT EASILY DAMAGED. RETRAINING IN WORK METHODS ON PROPER AND SAFE LOADING AND HANDLING OF HAZARDOUS MATERIALS, LIQUIDS AND CHEMICALS. RECURRENT TRAINING IN HAZARDOUS MATERIALS. WHEN LOADING NOTE THAT BAGS, PAILS OR DRUMS OF LIQUIDS AHEAD. HEAVY FREIGHT LOADED ON THE BOTTOM, LIGHT FREIGHT ON TOP! USE PLENTY OF CUSHIONING BETWEEN LAYERS OF FREIGHT. DO NOT LOAD HEAVY FREIGHT ON TOP OF HAZARDOUS MATERIALS. FREIGHT MUST BE SECURELY BLOCKED AND BRACED BEFORE ALLOWING TO MOVE IN TRANSIT!

column168: DART TRUCKING DRIVER CALLED THIS WRITER AT APPROXIMATELY 15:55 EST. REPORTED THAT UPON A CHECK OF HIS TRACTOR, TRAILER, AND LOAD, HE SMELLED THE HAZARDOUS MATERIAL.  DRIVER OPENED THE DOOR OF TRAILER AND DETECTED A LIQUID ON THE FLOOR OF TRAILER. DRIVER WAS NOT ABLE TO DETECT WHICH DRUM ON TRAILER WAS LEAKING.  THIS WRITER INSTRUCTED THE DRIVER TO NOTIFY THE STATE OF TEXAS UNDER DART TRUCKING'S CONTINGENCY PLAN.  DRIVER THEN INSTRUCTED TO CALL EMERGENCY RESPONSE NUMBER ON THE MANIFEST.  DRIVER DETECTED THE LIQUID ALSO DRIPPING FROM THE RIGHT CORNER OF THE TRAILER.  VEOLIA ES CONTACTED.  VEOLIA DISPATCHED A MITIGATION CREW TO CLEAN UP THE HAZ LEAKER.  SET ENVIRONMENTAL IS THE CLEAN UP COMPANY SENT OUT TO MITIGATE.  THEY FOUND LEAKING DRUM APPROX. 7:00PM. OVER PACKED THE LEAKING DRUM.  DRUM HAD PIN HOLE ON THE BOTTOM CLOSE TO CENTER OF DRUM.  CLEAN UP COMPLETED @ 19:45 EST.
column169: DART TRUCKING CO., INC. DRIVERS ARE TRAINED EXTENSIVELY IN OSHA HAZWOPER (40-HOUR), DOT FAMILIARIZATION & AWARENESS TRAINING, A CARGO SECUREMENT (SPECIFICALLY HAZ). TRAILER WAS LOADED FROM NOSE TO REAR WITH DRUMS OF HAZ WASTE.  IT WOULD HAVE BEEN IMPOSSIBLE FOR THE DRIVER TO DETECT THE PIN HOLE IN THE DRUM.  THERE WAS EXCELLENT SUCUREMENT OF THE LOAD.  NOTHING WAS IN CONTACT WITH ANYTHING ELSE.  THE LOAD OF WASTE WAS ON THE TRAILER FOR SEVERAL HUNDRED MILES WITH NO LEAK.  PIN HOLE HAD TO BE DUE TO WEAR (CORROSION, INTERIOR) THAT FINALLY BEGAN TO LEAK.

column168: The Eldredge, Inc. driver was driving west on Rt. 80 near MM 35 when he heard a loud pop as if he had a blow-out.  Instead the tanker had split in half and the hazardous material was released to the environment.  Approximately 4,300 gallons of the approximate 4,953 gallon load spilled onto the highway.  The driver was not injured and the tractor had no damage.  The leased comptank was towed back to Harold Marcus in Ontario, Canada, for inspection.    McCutcheon Enterprises, Inc. responded to the spill as did the Pennsylvania Dept. of Env. Protection (PADEP).  Soda ash was used to neutralize the corrosive material and approximately 7 yards of Residual waste was generated from the roadway cleanup and loaded into a roll-off container for future disposal.  Any puddles of liquid were neutralized onsite too.  Soil samples were taken and the area cleaned up had lower levels of RCRA metals than the background samples taken before and after the spill site.  A few wells were sampled in the area too and all results were fine so far.  Ongoing remediation and cleanup is being done by McCutcheon in conjuction with the PADEP Waste Management Section.    PENNDOT has requested samples of the highway so they may be tested by their laboratory for asphalt degradation.  This is also an ongoing project.
column169: Eldredge is currently re-evaluating the use of comptanks for hauling this waste material.  Eldredge may start using stainless steel tank trailers with a liner to haul this material in the future.

column168: According to the information obtained, the following occurred.  While making a delivery, approximately 20 gallons of gasoline were released as a result of a human error.  The United Transport of East Longmeadow, Inc. driver applied absorbent pads to contain the free liquid on the impacted asphalt surface.  The Springfield Fire Department and the Massachusetts Department of Environmental Protection responded to assess the scene.  The Springfield Fire Department applied absorbent material to further contain the free liquid on the impacted asphalt surface.  Western Mass Environmental of West Springfield, Massachusetts was dispatched to perform the remainder of the cleanup.     Western Mass Environmental recovered the contaminated absorbent material and applied additional absorbent material as needed.  One (1) 55-gallon drum of contaminated absorbent material was generated as a result of the cleanup.  Western Mass Environmental will coordinate disposal of the waste generated as a result of the incident.
column169: Since the release was accidental, no actions currently exist to prevent recurrence.  However, United Transport of East Longmeadow, Inc. will continue to reinforce safety guidelines and handling procedures to all personnel.

column168: Upon arrival, pallets (2) found to be heavily soiled and a strong, fruity aroma was observed.  The shipment consisted of cartons containing plastic jugs.  The jugs appear to have frozen and then thawed while in transit.  Upon freezing the seals on many of the jugs were broken and upon thawing residue leaked from the seals into the cartons.  It is estimated that 1 gallon of actual product was released.  The release was contained as the leaked product absorbed into the cardboard cartons.  The inner containers held the bulk of the product and the freight was kept right-side-up to prevent any additional release from the broken seals.
column169: Liquid product subject to freezing should not have been transported during the cold weather period.  The origin Conway location of XAH was notified and advised of the spill.  They will follow up with the shipper to ensure future shipments are not made in non-climate controlled vehicles during freezing weather.

column168: THE SHIPPER TENDERED THE SHIPMENT ON 12/19/09, HRZU873515-7/HON165166, TO LOAD IN LONGBEACH ONBOARD THE HORIZON RELIANCE,RG244S, FOR TRANSIT TO HONOLULU. ON 12/21/09, CHIEF MATE NOTED A FEW DROPS COMING FROM THE CONTAINER. IT WAS SETTING UP AS A CLEAR MATERIAL, DETERMINED TO BE RESIN UN1866/CLASS 3. APPROPIATE PRECAUTIONS WERE TAKEN AND PERTINENT PARTIES NOTIFIED. THE DROP/LEAKAGE STOPPED. ON DISCHARGE FROM VESSEL ON 12/23/09 NO LEAKAGE OCCURRED. CONTAINER WAS OBSERVED PRIOR TO RELEASE AND THERE WAS NO MORE ISSUE WITH THE CONTIANER. IT TOOK MORE TIME THEN EXPECTED TO CONNECT WITH APPROPIATE PERSON AT DELIVERY LOCATION TO GIVE FINAL INFORMATION TO THIS COMPLETE REPORT.
column169: IN LIGHT OF THIS EVENT, SHIPPER SHOULD INSPECT ALL LIDS FOR PROPER CLOSURE. SHIPPER SHOULD ALSO CONNECT WITH MANUFACTURER/PRODUCER TO HAVE THEM REVIEW THEIR COVER SEALING PROCEDURES TO ASSIST IN MAKING SURE LIDS ARE SECURE THROUGHOUT THE DRUMS TRANSIT.

column168: SHIPPER TENDERED PORTABLE TANK, DCIU947012-7/TX2905025, ON 12/23/09 IN HOUSTON FOR LOADING ON THE HORIZON DISCOVERY FOR TRANSIT TO SAN JUAN, PR. THE TANK WAS LOADED AND THE VESSEL SAILED. AFTER ARRIVAL IN SAN JUAN 12/19/09, IT WAS DISCOVERED VAPORS COMING FROM THE TANK. TANK WAS DISCHARGED AND MOVED TO A REMOTE LOCATION. PERTINENT PARTIES WERE NOTIFIED. SHIPPER HAD A TECHNICIAN ATTEND THE TANK AND INITIAL REPORTING INDICATED A FAULTY WELD. REGULATORY PARTIES WERE NOTIFIED AND A NRC REPORT (NO. 927355) WAS FILED. WITH ELAPSED TIME AT THE REMOTE STAGING AREA, VAPORS WERE NO LONGER EMITTED. UNDER LOCAL AUTHORITY SUPERVISION THE TANK WAS MOVED TO THE DESTINATION FACILITY FOR DISCHARGE. THIS FILING WAS AWAITING THE FINAL REPORT TO GIVE THE MOST ACCURATE INFORMATION, HOWEVER IT IS NOT AVAILABLE. THE QUANTITY RELEASED, VALUE OF LOST PRODUCT, AND RESPONSE COST ARE ESTIMATES. IN TODAY'S DIALOGUE WITH SHIPPER THEY INDICATED THE ACTUAL RELEASE WAS A RESULT OF OVER PRESSURIZING THE TANK, AND VAPOR RELEASE THROUGH SAFETY VALVE. THIS SMALLER TANK WAS NOT THE USUAL TANK USED FOR THIS PRODUCT AND SERVICE. IT HAS BEEN REMOVED FROM THIS SERVICE TO PREVENT ANY FUTURE RE-OCCURRENCE.
column169: IN LIGHT OF WHAT IS NOW INDICATED, THE SHIPPER MUST ENSURE THAT WHEN THESE TANKS OR ANY TANKS ARE FILLED, THE PERSONNEL IN CHARGE ARE WELL VERSED IN THE  TANK'S CAPACITY, IT'S LIMITATIONS, AND PROPER FILLING PROCEDURES.

column168: Unit 1 (Cargo Tank), reacted to Unit 2 (unknown car) that had spun out of control in front of Unit 1; in icy road conditions.  As a result of trying to avoid a collision unit 1 ended up in a jack-knife.  Unit 2 recovered and continued on without stopping at the scene.  Unit 1 and Unit 2 never made contact. Witnesses confirmed that unit 2 did spin out of control in front of unit 1.  In any event, the Cargo tank was empty returning from a delivery.  During the jack-knife the saddle tank on the tractor punctured and leaked its approximate 50 gallons of diesel fuel onto the ground. The Cargo tank did not leak any HM.  The road was closed for two hours while the truck and tanker were removed from the guardrail.  The tanker sustained a small dent in the #1 compartment, from the jack-knife, requiring it to be repaired.
column169: Unit 1 should have had better control of his unit.  As such speed control played an issue.  While unit 1 did not start the chain of events however he needed to react to them.  Possibly at a slower speed unit one would have had better control and not ended in a jack-knife.

column168: VEHICLE #1 WAS TRAVELING SOUTHWEST BOUND ON PULASKI HWY WHEN IT ROUNDED A CORNER AND MET A TRACTOR TRAILER #2 TRAVELING IN THE OPPOSITE DIRECTION IN THE PATH OF VEHICLE #1.  VEHICLE #1 SWERVED TO AVOID A COLLISION AND LOSS CONTROL.  ONCE VEHICLE #1 CLEARED VEHICLE #2 PASSENGER VEHICLES WERE NOW IN DANGER OF A COLLISION.  STILL SLIDING VEHICLE #1 WENT ONTO THE SOUTH SIDE SHOULDER AND OVERTURNED INTO THE DITCH.  THE ROLLOVER CAUSED DAMAGE TO THE HOSE REEL AND PIPING.  A PROPANE LEAK WAS DETECTED AND ALL PRECAUTIONS WERE TAKEN BY THE FIRE DEPT, DOT, HAZMAT, & POLICE DEPTS. THE ACCIDENT OCCURRED @ 10:32.  WE RECEIVED THE CALL @ 11:00 FROM THE ORANGE COUNTY CONTROL CENTER.  I DISPATCHED OUR SERVICE MANAGER TO THE SCENE.  OUR SERVICE MANAGER SENT ONE OF OUR DRIVERS TO THE ACCIDENT SCENE AS HE WAS IN THAT VICINITY.  OUR DRIVER ARRIVED ABOUT 11:20 AND SPOKE WITH THE AUTHORITIES.  HE WAS GIVEN PERMISSION TO APPROACH THE VEHICLE AND STOPPED THE LEAK BY CLOSING THE VALVES.  THE LEAK WAS ON THE 90 DEGREE SWIVEL JOINT LOCATED ON THE HOSE REEL.  A 1/4" FITTING BROKE OFF THE SWIVEL WHEN THE VEHICLE OVERTURNED.  THE LEAK LASTED ABOUT ONE HOUR.  THE LEAK WAS SLOWED BY THE GAS ICING INTO A SMALL BALL WHERE THE FITTING WAS LOCATED.  WE ESTIMATE APPROXIMATELY SEVEN GALLONS ESCAPED BEFORE THE LEAK WAS STOPPED.

column168: METRO ADVISED OF AN ACCIDENT INVOLVING A LARGE PROPANE TRUCK LEAKING, THE ON SCENE STATE POLICE ERO IS REQUESTING GALLUP FIRE HAZ MAT TEAM RESPONSE/ASSISTANCE. column168: THIS INCIDENT OCCURRED DURING THE END PHRASE OF UNLOADING SUPPLY TRUCK INTO RECEIVING UNIT:  TRUCK BODY MOUNT TANK.  IT WAS STRICTLY AN OVERFILL INCIDENT, NO EQUIPMENT FAILURE.  I WAS ALSONE.  I WAS MONITORING ANY HOSES AT THE TIME OF OVERFILL.  I WAS WATCHING THE HOSES AND EQUIPMENT MAKING SURE THERE WAS NO MALFUNCTION OR DISCONNECT, FULLY EXPECTING THE ORDER TO BE CONTAINED IN THE RECEIVING TANK.  I HAD BEEN WATCHING THE RECEIVING TRUCK, AND WHILE MAKING MY PERIODIC CHECKS, TURNED BACK TO THE RECEIVING TRUCK TO SEE IT OVERFLOWING, AND BY THE TIME I GOT THINGS SHUT DOWN, THE SUPPLY TRUCK WAS EMPTY.  NO ACTION WAS TAKEN TO MITIGATE.  I ASSUMED IT WOULD BE CONTAINED WHERE THE TRUCK WAS LOCATED.
column169: I HAVE HAD SEVERAL DISCUSSIONS ABOUT THIS INCIDENT WITH MY SAFETY DIRECTOR (GLENN HILLYER), AND HAVE RESOLVED TO MAKE THE FOLLOWING IMPROVEMENTS:  1. I WILL NOT DELIVER FUEL TO LOCATIONS AND EQUIPMENT SIMILAR TO THIS WITHOUT ANOTHER INDIVIDUAL THERE TO ASSIST ME, AS PER GUIDELINES AND REQUIREMENTS. 2. I WILL NOT RELY ON THE ORDER TO BE CONTAINED IN THE RECEIVING UNIT. 3. I WILL IMMEDIATELY NOTIFY AND MAKE EFFORT TO CONTAIN.  4. I WILL DO EVERYTHING IN MY POWER TO PREVENT ANOTHER INCIDENT, BY FAMILIARIZING MYSELF WITH NEW (TO ME) EQUIPMENT, AND WORKING TO UNDERSTAND ITS LIMITATIONS.

column168: On December 8th, 2009, Seaboard Marine was advised by the shipper that undeclared hazardous materials were stowed inside container FSCU658172, scheduled to sail under booking MIA2330213. The container had been transported by road to Seaboard Marine's Port of Miami terminal and was on terminal grounds at the time we (Seaboard Marine) received notice that undeclared hazardous cargoes had been loaded. In addition to the UN1950 Aerosols, there were also 15 Fiberboard boxes of UN1993, Flammable Liquid N.O.S. (Contains Methanol), Class 3,PG III stowed in the container. All items were in Limited Quantities.Upon receiving notice of the undeclared hazardous cargo inside of FSCU658172, we (Seaboard Marine) immediately placed a "Hold" on the container and prohibited future movement. The shipper provided Seaboard Marine with the proper documentation describing all the hazardous materials inside of the container. The container was then placarded accordingly and released for transport.
column169: Enhanced education towards the shipping industry is necessary. Anyone who opens a business should attend a mandatory course where general shipping methods and practices are discussed. This course would include a general awareness portion on hazardous materials.

column168: FARMER CHALES ENTZ WAS PULLING THE ANHYDROUS AMMONIA NURSE TRAILER TO HIS FARM.  CHARLES TURNED LEFT AT THE INTERSECTION OF MAIN ST. AND HIGHWAY 196 ON THE SOUTH SIDE OF WHITEWATER.  THE HIGHWAY HAS A CROWN I N THE CENTER WHICH CAUSED THE ANHYDROUS AMMONIA INSIDE THE TANK TO SHIFT RAPIDLY TO THE RIGHT.  THE SHIFTING WEIGHT BROKE A METAL FREE OF THE RUNNING GEAR.  THE TANK STRUCK THE PAVEMENT AND ROLLED TOWARDS THE SOUTH DITCH.  THE FORCE OF THE TANK STRIKING THE PAVEMENT BENT THE METAL GUARD SURROUNDING THE PRESSURE RELIEF VALVE.  THE PRV WAS BENT IN THE THREADS AND BEGAN LEAKING ANHYDROUS AMMONIA VAPORS.  CHARLES PULLED THE DAMAGED RUNNING GEAR BACK TO THE WHITEWATER OFFICE TO REPORT THE ACCIDENT.  LOCATION MANAGER TOM BECK DROVE TO THE SCENE AND PROCEEDED TO CALL 911, THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER, KANSAS EMERGENCY MANAGEMENT, BUTLER COUNTY LEPC.  HAZMAT CREWS RESPONDED TO THE SCENE.  THE LOCAL FIRE DEPT. APPLIED A FOG OF WATER TO THE LEAKING ANHYDROUS AMMONIA VAPORS.  THE WIND WAS FROM THE SOUTH AT 6-10 MPH.  THE WATER FOG KNOCKED DOWN AND CONTAINED THE LEAKING ANHYDROUS VAPORS SO NO EVACAUTIONS WERE NECESSARY.  AN EMPTY ANHYDROUS AMMONIA TRAILER WAS POSITIONED ALONG SIDE THE LEAKING NURSE TANK.  A HOSE WAS CONNECTED BETWEEN THE TWO TANKS TO VAPOR TRANSFER AS MUCH ANHYDROUS AS POSSIBLE.  AFTER 40% OF THE ANHYDROUS AMMONIA HAD BEEN TRANSFERRED THE PRESSURE IN THE LEAKING TANK HAD DROPPED TO THE POINT WHERE NO MORE VAPORS WERE LEAKING.  A WRECKER TRUCK WAS USED TO LIFT THE DAMAGED NURSE TANK ONTO A FLAT BED TRAILER.  THE DAMAGED TANK WAS TRANSPORTED BACK TO THE ANYDROUS AMMONIA PLANT WHERE THE REMAINING PRODUCT WAS PUMPED BACK INTO THE BULK STORAGE TANK.
column169: New running gears have been ordered to replace older running gears in the fleet. A through inspection is being conducted of all the remaining running gear to check for broken welds and elongated anchor bolts.

column168: Our transport turned south off Hwy 72 onto Hwy 25., traveled approx. one mile to accident. It was dark and our driver could not see an empty log trailer lying across the  highway, blocking both lanes. Upon impact, our truck and trailer overturned, spilling  approx. 3225 gallons of Unleaded Regular Gasoline at a slow flow. Gasoline leaked  through bulkhead into void space between compartments. Duration of leak is  undetermined but could be up to 4 or 5 hours. To mitigate the problem, US  Environmental Services were called to respond, local law and state law officials, fire  departments and any parties of concern. US Environment Services stopped leaking tank  and completed a very good cleanup. As we sent two other transports to remove remaining gasoline from wrecked tanker. Wrecked vehicle was then removed.
column169: Our transport drivers are thoroughly trained in every aspect for transporting hazardous materials before being dispatched. They also receive continuous training of hazmat and safe driving. We do mit know of any additional training that could have facilitated avoiding this accident. No one would ever expect a log truck to turn out onto a highway without his trailer properly latched, thus dumping his trailer across both lanes of the highway in a pitch dark night.

column168: This shipment was initially offered on 12/10/2009 as containing perfume. That shipment was rejected as it was not offered as a dangerous goods.  We did not notify FAA as it fell under the constructive knowledge principle.  On 12/11/2009, this shipper re-offered the freight as body oil.  The box was opened to reveal a 1.7-oz bottle of Banana Republic's "W" perfume.  There were no markings, labeling, shipping papers, emergency response information nor other indicators to lead us to believe the contents were regulated.  The FAA was notified, I spoke to Hazmat Manager Earl Andresen.  The case has since been turned over to SA Justin Bobko.  The freight is being held for an FAA inspection or when pictures can be taken.  The shipper has been telephonically notified, he has yet to respond to my call.

column168: DURING THE PACKAGE SORTING OPERATION ON DEC 18,2009, EMPLOYEES IN THE LAWNSIDE, NJ UPS FACILITY NOTICED A PACKAGE HAD CAUGHT FIRE. CONTENTS OF THE BURNED PACKAGE WERE FOUND TO BE SEVERAL AEROSOLS OF PERSONAL DEODORANT, SOME OF WHICH WERE MISSING THEIR CAPS.  IT IS BELIEVED THAT WITHOUT CAPS ONE OR MORE OF THE AERSOLS HAD DISCHARGED FLAMMABLE CONTENTS.  UPS CONVEYOR SYSTEMS ARE KNOWN TO GENERATE STATIC ELECTRICITY AND A STATIC SPARK IS LIKELY TO HAVE IGNITED THE FLAMMABLE GAS VAPORTS DISCHARGED FROM THE PACKAGE.
column169: PACKAGING OF AEROSOLS TO KEEP PROTECTIVE CAPS IN PLACE WOULD PREVENT THE ACCIDENTAL DISCHARGE OF THE CONTENTS.

Shipper: INDIVIDUAL NOT A COMPANY, 2714 Evergreen Ct, Mays Landing, NJ 08330   AWB# 7822245465                                                                          On 12/03/2009, DHL driver Joe Smith contacted the DHL station to advise that he had picked up four packages from the above listed shipper, but didn't believe the contents matched the description on the airwaybill.  DHL Station Supervisor, Daniel Weaver, advised that he would look at the shipments when they arrived.   Upon arrival at DHL, Daniel Weaver recognized shipper's name and address (different from that on the airwaybill) as being someone that tendered a credit card fraud-related shipment to DHL in the past.  It was discovered shipper (Cheri Nelson) was offering DHL a "recycled airwaybill" that had been used for a package destined for same receiver on an earlier date.  Daniel Weaver contacted the DHL Express Fraud Department to advise and awaited their instruction.                                                                        On 12/28/2009, Daniel Weaver contacted our International Dangerous Goods Hotline in regard to these 4 packages and their contents which consists of 44 gift sets containing 170.6 ounces.  Shipper did not tender packages to DHL, marked or labeled as a Dangerous Goods, nor did they provide a Shipper's Declaration.  Daniel was provided with documentation to complete in regard to the contents of the package and was asked to provide pictures.  Shipment did not travel via aircraft, although it was tendered to DHL to do as such.
